  "doc_id": "60192",
  "text": "The changing of a parasitic interaction from a severe state to one where hosts tolerate parasites has considerable epidemiological, evolutionary, and coevolutionary consequences [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ). For example, theoretical work has indicated that increases in host tolerance, even when leading to the evolution of less harmful parasites, tends ultimately to increase disease prevalence and the overall amount of mortality a population suffers [CITATION_4] ; this is the tragedy of tolerance. This conclusion holds for an obligate killer such as P. ramosa. We modeled parasite evolution (for model details, see app. B) and considered different forms of the relationship between parasite population growth (l) and host mortality rate (a; fig. 3 ): a positive relationship (i.e., harshly parasitic), an essentially flat relationship, and one where the relationship is slightly negative.",
